04701nam a22006975i 9780674040083DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20092004mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740400837 a10.4159/97806740400832doi  a(DE-B1597)590385  a(OCoLC)1294427027  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a302.2309471 aLenoe, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCloser to the Masses :bStalinist Culture, Social Revolution, and Soviet Newspapers /cMatthew Lenoe. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2009] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (325 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRussian Research Center Studies ;v9500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tI SOVIET NEWSPAPERS IN THE 1920S -- t1 Agitation, Propaganda, and the NEP Mass Enlightenment Project -- t2 Newspaper Distribution and the Emergence of Soviet Information Rationing -- t3 Reader Response and Its Impact on the Press -- tII THE CREATION OF MASS JOURNALISM AND SOCIALIST REALISM -- t4 The Creation of Mass Journalism -- t5 Mass Journalists, "Cultural Revolution," and the Retargeting of Soviet Newspapers -- t6 The Central Committee and Self-Criticism, 1928-1929 -- t7 Mass Journalism, "Soviet Sensations," and Socialist Realism -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Notes to Tables -- tArchival Sources -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this provocative book, Matthew Lenoe traces the origins of Stalinist mass culture to newspaper journalism in the late 1920s. In examining the transformation of Soviet newspapers during the New Economic Policy and the First Five Year Plan, Lenoe tells a dramatic story of purges, political intrigues, and social upheaval. Under pressure from the party leadership to mobilize society for the monumental task of industrialization, journalists shaped a master narrative for Soviet history and helped create a Bolshevik identity for millions of new communists. Everyday labor became an epic battle to modernize the USSR, a fight not only against imperialists from outside, but against shirkers and saboteurs within. Soviet newspapermen mobilized party activists by providing them with an identity as warrior heroes battling for socialism. Yet within the framework of propaganda directives, the rank-and-file journalists improvised in ways that ultimately contributed to the creation of a culture. The images and metaphors crafted by Soviet journalists became the core of Stalinist culture in the mid-1930s, and influenced the development of socialist realism. Deeply researched and lucidly written, this book is a major contribution to the literature on Soviet culture and society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCommunism and culturezSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPress and propagandazSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aSocialist realismxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674040083?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674040083423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674040083/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aP